rule_descriptions.rule_description: The result of the evaluation of an expression shall not depend on the order of evaluation of subexpressions. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.5)
Implicit function declaration shall not be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.5.1p2)
Enumerators shall have a value representable as an int. (ISO/IEC 9899:2011 6.7.2.2p2+3)
No implicit conversion shall be performed between pointer types and integer types. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.5.4p3)
No initializer shall attempt to provide a value for an object not contained within the entity being initialized. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.7.8p2)
Lvalue casts shall be avoided. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
A struct type shall have at least one member. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.7.2.1)
Pointer arithmetic shall not be applied to pointer to incomplete type. (ISO/IEC 9899:2011 6.5.6p2+3)
Directives are required to follow the syntax and constraints specified in the manual.
At least one type specifier shall be given in a declaration. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.7.2p2)
Language features not supported by Astree should be avoided.
Non-standard keywords shall not be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
If the size expression of an array declarator is constant, it shall have a value greater than zero. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.7.5.2p1)
GCC's statement expressions shall not be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
The constant expression of a static assert shall compare unequal to zero. (ISO/IEC 9899:2011 6.7.10p2)
The result of the evaluation of an initializer list expression shall not depend on the order of evaluation of elements and subexpressions. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.7.8)
Pointer attributes shall be avoided. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
Identifiers containing characters not provided for by the C standard shall not be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.4.2.1)
The lvalue of a unary or binary assignment operator shall be a modifiable lvalue. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.5.16p2)
Two declarations that declare the same entity must be of compatible type. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.2.7p2)
Enums shall not be forward-declared, i.e. used as complete type before being defined. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
The alignment specifier _Alignas shall only be used as specified by the C standard. (ISO/IEC 9899:2011 6.7.5)
Every parameter identifier in a function definition with identifier-list shall be declared. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.9.1p6)
Data placement at an absolute location shall be avoided. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
The number of arguments shall agree with the number of parameters. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.5.2.2p2)
Non-standard escape sequences shall not be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.4.4.4)
GCC's #include_next directive shall not be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
The compiler-specific __packed__ type specifier shall not be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
Analyzer configuration.
GCC's binary constants shall not be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
The value of an integer character constant containing more than one character is implementation-defined. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.4.4.4p10)
If an identifier has no linkage, there shall be no more than one declaration of the identifier with the same scope and in the same name space, except for tags. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.7p3)
No cast shall be performed between pointer types and integer types. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.3.2.3p5+6)
A bit-field shall have a type _Bool, signed int, unsigned int, or some other implementation-defined type. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.7.2.1)
__attribute__((...)) and __attribute((...)) shall not be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
The include file checking macros __has_include and __has_include_next shall not be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
Compiler-specific builtin functions shall not be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
Clang warnings.
Only integer constant expressions stricly conforming to the C standard shall be used. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.6p10)
A return statement shall only define a return value if and only if the containing function has non-void return type. (ISO/IEC 9899:2011 6.8.6.4p1)
A pointer type shall not be implicitly converted into an incompatible pointer type. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 6.5.16.1p1)
The sizeof and _Alignof operator shall not be applied to type void. (ISO/IEC 9899:2011 6.5.3.4p1)
Assembler code shall be avoided. (ISO/IEC 9899:1999 4p5)
Language features not supported by Astree that are discarded by the frontend should be avoided.

check_descriptions.check_description: Pointer attributes shall be avoided.
If the size expression of an array declarator is constant, it shall have a value greater than zero.
__attribute__((...)) and __attribute((...)) shall not be used.
Functions shall not be declared implicitly.
The condition of _Static_assert shall be a constant expression.
The lvalue to which an assignment is applied to shall be a modifiable lvalue.
A (function) pointer type shall not be implicitly converted into an incompatible (function) pointer type.
Unsupported language features shall not be used.
A cast shall not be performed between a pointer to object type and an integral type.
The values of initializer lists shall not depend on the order of evaluation of its elements and their subexpressions.
If objects or functions are declared more than once their types shall be compatible.
Memory areas declared with absolute addresses shall not partially overlap.
Conversions shall not be performed between a pointer to a function and an integer type.
A struct type shall have at least one member.
Poitner arithmetic shall not be used with pointers to void.
The include file checking macro __has_include_next shall not be used.
The compiler-specific type specifier __packed__ shall not be used.
Non-standard escape sequences shall not be used.
The compiler-specific builtin function __builtin_constant_p() shall not be used.
The sizeof operator shall not be applied to type void.
Warning issued by the clang frontend
In functions with void return type, a return statement shall not define a return value.
Directives that do not comply with the constraints are dropped by the frontend.
GCC's statement expressions shall be avoided.
GCC's binary constants shall be avoided.
Every variable declaration statement shall comprise the data type.
The value of an enumerator shall be representable as a signed int.
Character constant containing more than one c-char.
An array initializer shall not exceed the size of the object initialized.
Enums shall not be forward-declared.
Lvalue casts shall be avoided.
Language features that are not supported by the analyzer shall not be used.
Non-standard keywords shall not be used.
The alignment specifier _Alignas shall only be used as specified by the C standard.
Entities with no linkage shall not be redeclared in the same scope.
Bitfields shall be of signed or unsigned integer type.
The compiler-specific builtin function __builtin_sel() shall not be used.
Conversions shall not be performed between a pointer to a function and an integer type.
The include file checking macro __has_include shall not be used.
The value of an expression and its persistent side effects shall be the same under all evaluation orders.
An Implicit cast shall not be performed between a pointer to object type and an integral type.
An object pointer type shall not be implicitly converted into an incompatible object pointer type.
#include_next directives shall be avoided.
If objects or functions are declared more than once their types shall be compatible.
The _Alignof operator shall not be applied to type void.
Intervals specified in directives shall not exceed the range of values of the affected type.
AAL annotations shall address valid source locations.
Identifiers containing characters not provided for by the C standard shall not be used.
In functions with non-void return type, a return statement shall define a return value.
Every parameter identifier in a function definition with identifier-list shall be declared.
A function definition shall comprise the return type.
The number of arguments at a function call shall match the number of parameters according to the type of the function designator.
Only stricly conforming constant expressions shall be used.
Rule checks which depend on an analysis phase which is not active cannot be executed.
Assembler code shall be avoided.
Data placement at an absolute address using @ notation shall be avoided.
The constant expression of a static assert (_Static_assert) shall compare unequal to zero.
#pragma directives shall only be used in the specified manner.
